1
00:00:04,240 --> 00:00:07,199
A film by Manoel de Oliveira

2
00:00:07,841 --> 00:00:12,040
OPORTO OF MY CHILDHOOD
"To my children"

3
00:03:28,301 --> 00:03:30,373
Producer

4
00:03:31,463 --> 00:03:33,533
Director and voice off

5
00:03:35,744 --> 00:03:40,262
To recall moments from a distant past
is to travel out of time

6
00:03:40,746 --> 00:03:45,867
Only each person's memory can do
this. It is what I shall try to do.

7
00:03:49,309 --> 00:03:53,666
This is nothing more than the ghost
of the house where I was born.

8
00:03:54,030 --> 00:03:59,025
A fatal ruin, a final vision,
with nothing surprising for anyone...

9
00:03:59,871 --> 00:04:03,627
But to one for whom it was
the cradle in which he grew up,

10
00:04:03,913 --> 00:04:06,712
where he became aware of himself
and of the world,

11
00:04:07,153 --> 00:04:10,591
a painful longing
remains in his soul.

12
00:04:12,475 --> 00:04:16,071
Oh, how many years ago
Did I depart in tears

13
00:04:16,516 --> 00:04:19,827
From my cosy
Caring home

14
00:04:20,357 --> 00:04:24,192
Twenty, Thirty?
Do I not even know when

15
00:04:24,519 --> 00:04:28,149
My old nanny
You who are watching me

16
00:04:28,680 --> 00:04:31,957
Sing me songs
So I may remember

17
00:04:32,601 --> 00:04:35,719
I have been around the world
I have been around life

18
00:04:36,123 --> 00:04:39,719
I only found cheating
Deception, sorrow

19
00:04:40,044 --> 00:04:43,560
Oh! How disillusioned
Is the innocent soul

20
00:04:43,845 --> 00:04:47,521
My old nanny
With your doleful voice

21
00:04:47,766 --> 00:04:51,646
Sing me songs
To set me to sleep

22
00:04:52,888 --> 00:04:57,917
In front of the proud house
there rose three leafy lindens,

23
00:04:58,369 --> 00:05:03,205
the protectors of a beautiful
garden, the Eden of my boyhood.

24
00:05:05,211 --> 00:05:08,522
My heart is broken
With bitterness

25
00:05:08,853 --> 00:05:12,607
See what deep pain lies
In my misty gaze

26
00:05:12,853 --> 00:05:16,483
Oh, had I never left
My narrow nest

27
00:05:16,975 --> 00:05:20,491
My old nanny
Sing me songs

28
00:05:20,976 --> 00:05:15,050
Sing me songs
To lull me to sleep

29
00:05:26,258 --> 00:05:32,016
From high up at the windows
one enjoyed a vast view of the city.

30
00:05:32,580 --> 00:05:36,369
God once gave me in
The down of the nest

31
00:05:36,620 --> 00:05:39,852
Precious stones from stars
Gems of moonlight

32
00:05:40,141 --> 00:05:43,771
See, I have been robbed of
Everything along the way

33
00:05:44,023 --> 00:05:47,539
My old nanny
I am a wretched poor man

34
00:05:47,784 --> 00:05:51,619
Sing me songs
To make me cry

35
00:05:54,746 --> 00:05:57,784
Like once before
In the beloved lap

36
00:05:57,987 --> 00:06:01,185
I am dying, dying
Let me rest!

37
00:06:01,429 --> 00:06:04,819
Oh, how your little boy
Has changed

38
00:06:05,069 --> 00:06:08,983
My old nanny
How he has changed

39
00:06:09,471 --> 00:06:13,510
Sing him songs to sleep
To dream

40
00:06:14,672 --> 00:06:18,063
Sing me songs, softly
So, so softly

41
00:06:18,313 --> 00:06:22,193
Sad, so sad
Like the sea at night

42
00:06:22,435 --> 00:06:25,951
Sing me songs to see
If I can manage

43
00:06:36,356 --> 00:06:30,350
To make my soul sleep
Be at peace, at rest

44
00:06:30,877 --> 00:06:34,188
When soon Death
Comes to take it from me

45
00:06:38,600 --> 00:06:43,436
Once, a long time ago, there was
only one birth there, mine,

46
00:06:44,121 --> 00:06:46,841
there was only one death there,
that of my father.

47
00:06:48,082 --> 00:06:51,075
The years have passed
and the times have changed.

48
00:06:52,484 --> 00:06:55,556
Everything has been taken,
everything has been forgotten.

49
00:06:56,124 --> 00:06:00,244
It only remains alive
in my sad memory.

50
00:07:05,207 --> 00:07:12,764
''Eu sou toureiro, toureador
Bandarilheiro, farpeador... ''

51
00:07:39,938 --> 00:07:43,819
My parents had a season ticket
to the opera,

52
00:07:44,179 --> 00:07:46,899
and had another box
at the Sá da Bandeira Theatre.

53
00:07:47,540 --> 00:07:50,533
I remember this scene
from the operetta Miss Diabo,

54
00:07:50,941 --> 00:07:55,971
by the distinguished Oporto authors
Arnaldo Leite and Carvalho Barbosa,

55
00:07:57,304 --> 00:08:01,503
just as I saw it
from box number 16.

56
00:08:33,474 --> 00:08:34,828
Hands up!

57
00:08:36,435 --> 00:08:39,428
- Hands up!
- And the step backwards...

58
00:08:40,916 --> 00:08:42,509
I fell in like a duck!

59
00:08:43,157 --> 00:08:44,432
Hands up!

60
00:08:45,918 --> 00:08:49,879
Okay Madame!
You'd better point that away,

61
00:08:50,160 --> 00:08:51,593
it might be loaded

62
00:08:52,400 --> 00:08:54,676
and I don't want to march off
to the angels...

63
00:09:05,644 --> 00:09:07,362
Would you like one, Madame?

64
00:09:31,292 --> 00:09:35,764
Don't worry, Madame, this
won't kill anyone from a distance.

65
00:10:03,901 --> 00:10:05,415
This is a real good smoke!

66
00:10:10,183 --> 00:10:14,224
Put that thing away and
let me suck this beauty in peace.

67
00:10:15,465 --> 00:10:18,458
That tool wasn't made
for lady's fingers...

68
00:10:20,026 --> 00:10:21,346
Put that down!

69
00:10:22,707 --> 00:10:24,141
Will you put it down or not?

70
00:10:31,270 --> 00:10:32,783
Who lives here?

71
00:10:34,951 --> 00:10:37,749
My father, the servants and me.

72
00:10:37,992 --> 00:10:41,588
And the dog that almost
ruined my trousers...

73
00:10:42,794 --> 00:10:45,706
What now?
Are you going to call the police?

74
00:10:46,434 --> 00:10:48,471
No, I'm not.

75
00:10:49,035 --> 00:10:52,393
In fact I thank you for coming.
I have finally seen a...

76
00:10:53,076 --> 00:10:57,390
A thief? You can say it.
I don't stand on ceremony...

77
00:10:58,878 --> 00:11:02,839
But, what's this?
Bravo, we have music!

78
00:11:13,282 --> 00:11:17,197
- Do you play?
- I scratch a little. It's obligatory.

79
00:11:18,044 --> 00:11:19,637
I was born in the Moorish Quarter.

80
00:11:26,607 --> 00:11:32,080
Criminal hands
Sad rejected hands

81
00:11:33,048 --> 00:11:35,483
Capricious
Desolate

82
00:11:36,210 --> 00:11:38,770
Hands of hunger
And bitterness

83
00:11:39,970 --> 00:11:45,490
Criminal hands
Sad rejected hands

84
00:11:46,373 --> 00:11:48,682
Capricious
Desolate

85
00:11:49,333 --> 00:11:51,894
Hands of hunger
And bitterness

86
00:11:52,814 --> 00:11:55,204
Hands of Fado singers

87
00:11:55,575 --> 00:11:59,092
Who never sought
A sweet kiss from you

88
00:11:59,736 --> 00:12:04,653
Hands to whom I give
All my impure life

89
00:12:05,418 --> 00:12:10,733
Chilly hands
Poor, frightened hands

90
00:12:11,780 --> 00:12:17,095
Foreboding, aching hands
Now weary of suffering

91
00:12:17,902 --> 00:12:20,019
Hands of wretchedness

92
00:12:20,223 --> 00:12:24,058
That sob out a Fado song
On the guitar...

93
00:12:24,504 --> 00:12:30,263
Hands that freeze
And that Death will forget

94
00:12:30,826 --> 00:12:33,705
I remember the Hanging Tree,

95
00:12:34,027 --> 00:12:37,304
which at the time existed
in the Cordoaria Gardens.

96
00:12:38,068 --> 00:12:41,426
And I used to ask whether thieves
were also hanged there.

97
00:12:42,030 --> 00:12:43,509
I never got an answer.

98
00:12:45,871 --> 00:12:50,070
I was afraid. And in the
dark night, seized by fear,

99
00:12:50,952 --> 00:12:54,582
I found security in hearing
the horse guard go by.

100
00:13:09,238 --> 00:13:12,196
I don't know whether it was
to chase away my fear of thieves

101
00:13:12,559 --> 00:13:16,313
or through a desire to travel
through the deserted streets at night,

102
00:13:16,840 --> 00:13:19,230
I asked if we could take
the long way home.

103
00:13:19,761 --> 00:13:22,151
My mother indulged me
in my whim,

104
00:13:24,722 --> 00:13:27,079
and told the chauffeur to do so.

105
00:13:29,684 --> 00:13:31,356
The chauffeur's name was...

106
00:13:31,564 --> 00:13:35,523
Lamas.
The chauffeur was called Lamas.

107
00:13:35,886 --> 00:13:38,924
Lamas, that's it!
His name was Lamas!

108
00:15:47,965 --> 00:15:52,961
This is the street were
my long-gone house used to exist.

109
00:15:53,367 --> 00:16:00,286
It is named the 9th of July,
because, on the 9th of July 1832,

110
00:16:00,649 --> 00:16:03,039
King Dom Pedro IV's troops
came along this street,

111
00:16:03,250 --> 00:16:06,926
having disembarked on Mindelo
Beach on the previous day.

112
00:16:08,572 --> 00:16:11,132
This is King Dom Pedro IV,
the Liberator,

113
00:16:11,493 --> 00:16:14,327
who left his heart to Oporto,

114
00:16:14,653 --> 00:16:17,726
the City that was the birthplace
of the Liberty of the Nation.

115
00:16:48,264 --> 00:16:51,814
Almeida Garrett,
a poet and a liberal from Oporto,

116
00:16:52,505 --> 00:16:57,022
disembarked with King Don Pedro's
troops. And he sang like this.

117
00:16:58,627 --> 00:17:02,860
''When I dreamt, it was like this
That I saw it in my dream

118
00:17:03,308 --> 00:17:05,265
''It was like this that the fleeting

119
00:17:05,589 --> 00:17:09,504
''Image that I could never reach
Would flee from me

120
00:17:10,830 --> 00:17:15,304
''Now that I am awake,
Now that I see it stare...

121
00:17:15,792 --> 00:17:20,026
''What for? When it was vague,
An idea, a thought,

122
00:17:20,514 --> 00:17:24,348
''An uncertain shine of star
In an immense firmament,

123
00:17:25,115 --> 00:17:30,510
''A chimera, a vain dream
I dreamt, but I lived

124
00:17:31,798 --> 00:17:37,715
''I knew not what pleasure was
But pain, I felt it not... ''

125
00:17:40,279 --> 00:17:44,035
With my head pressed against the
glass of one of those windows,

126
00:17:44,281 --> 00:17:48,241
looking at the city, I sometimes
thought of the beggars

127
00:17:48,442 --> 00:17:51,321
who asked for alms
outside Sunday Mass,

128
00:17:51,963 --> 00:17:55,877
and I saw myself with my hand
outstretched like them,

129
00:17:56,125 --> 00:17:57,478
next to my mother.

130
00:18:03,166 --> 00:18:08,481
And I saw myself as naturally as I
had seen the actors in the theatre.

131
00:18:12,089 --> 00:18:14,479
I also heard of someone

132
00:18:14,730 --> 00:18:19,407
who had fallen into disgrace
and wretchedness. And I thought...

133
00:18:20,292 --> 00:18:22,761
What if a similar misfortune
befalls us?

134
00:18:23,492 --> 00:18:26,645
I added a thousand
other possible misfortunes,

135
00:18:26,894 --> 00:18:30,888
which clouded my mind
like breath on the glass.

136
00:18:31,775 --> 00:18:34,370
And then I thought
that I could perhaps

137
00:18:34,616 --> 00:18:37,256
work as an apprentice stonemason.

138
00:18:37,737 --> 00:18:42,209
It was a tradition
passed down from father to son.

139
00:18:42,699 --> 00:18:44,576
I liked to watch them work.

140
00:18:46,260 --> 00:18:51,779
But could I do it? I still remember
the song they hummed,

141
00:18:52,021 --> 00:18:54,252
when they were dragging
a large stone

142
00:18:54,582 --> 00:18:57,734
and they moved it
with long iron poles,

143
00:18:58,503 --> 00:19:04,819
two men on each side,
as if rowing rhythmically.

144
00:19:06,066 --> 00:19:08,979
Stone... oh!
Stone... hey!

145
00:19:09,786 --> 00:19:12,779
Stone... oh!
Stone... hey!

146
00:19:14,908 --> 00:19:17,104
The profession
of these honest stonemasons,

147
00:19:17,389 --> 00:19:18,982
as humble as it is noble.

148
00:19:19,910 --> 00:19:22,823
In those days all the houses
were built of stone.

149
00:19:23,031 --> 00:19:24,828
A beautiful tradition
that is now lost,

150
00:19:25,111 --> 00:19:29,743
as can be seen
in the old houses and palaces,

151
00:19:30,433 --> 00:19:34,791
and in what remains of
the old wall around the city.

152
00:19:40,676 --> 00:19:43,874
As sweet-toothed as I was,
when they used to take me

153
00:19:44,077 --> 00:19:45,829
to the confectioner's shops
in the afternoon,

154
00:19:46,038 --> 00:19:49,236
I used to hide,
hoping to be left behind,

155
00:19:49,559 --> 00:19:52,757
and to be able to enjoy
all those pastries.

156
00:19:54,320 --> 00:19:58,076
The Confeitaria Oliveira
a cake-shop was my favourite

157
00:19:58,562 --> 00:20:00,792
and was considered
to be the most chic.

158
00:20:02,322 --> 00:20:04,633
But I wasn't attracted
by the luxury...

159
00:20:05,724 --> 00:20:07,794
- It was the pastries!
- It was the pastries.

160
00:20:09,405 --> 00:20:11,043
There were the ''babás''and others.

161
00:20:11,886 --> 00:20:14,605
But the puff pastries
with egg-paste filling,

162
00:20:14,847 --> 00:20:18,636
the ones they called ''cocós''
those were really good.

163
00:20:33,052 --> 00:20:34,645
Those pastries are delicious!

164
00:20:35,813 --> 00:20:38,930
But the cake-shop disappeared,
and the cakes went with it.

165
00:20:39,454 --> 00:20:41,126
This is it today.

166
00:20:45,295 --> 00:20:49,449
I'm just remembering
a curious episode I witnessed.

167
00:21:40,491 --> 00:21:41,411
At that time the tradition was

168
00:21:41,411 --> 00:21:42,891
At that time the tradition was

169
00:21:43,132 --> 00:21:45,600
to have two exhibitions
at the Crystal Palace,

170
00:21:45,852 --> 00:21:48,413
the Motor Show
and the Flower Show.

171
00:22:56,255 --> 00:22:59,374
Because of their similarity
and being stopped at rest,

172
00:22:59,576 --> 00:23:06,768
this is certainly the poets Fernando
Pessoa, on the left, and José Régio.

173
00:23:22,423 --> 00:23:25,542
Another tradition
was the after-dinner stroll,

174
00:23:26,304 --> 00:23:28,341
a back and forth
along the Avenida das Tilias,

175
00:23:29,025 --> 00:23:32,144
where it was chic
for the society ladies

176
00:23:32,427 --> 00:23:34,782
to show off their dresses
in the latest fashions.

177
00:23:38,228 --> 00:23:41,779
There were some houses opposite
the Crystal Palace gardens.

178
00:23:42,029 --> 00:23:45,068
In one of them, which belonged
to my uncle Casimiro,

179
00:23:45,590 --> 00:23:49,061
I stayed along with brother,
his godson,

180
00:23:49,631 --> 00:23:54,388
living with my cousins
while my parents travelled abroad.

181
00:23:55,473 --> 00:23:59,353
- My cousins were...
- António and his sisters...

182
00:23:59,634 --> 00:24:00,749
Virginia,

183
00:24:00,995 --> 00:24:01,872
Alice,

184
00:24:02,075 --> 00:24:03,031
Amélia,

185
00:24:03,276 --> 00:24:04,231
Maria,

186
00:24:04,476 --> 00:24:05,875
Guilhermina,

187
00:24:06,077 --> 00:24:07,031
and Helena.

188
00:24:07,237 --> 00:24:08,796
Of the three youngest ones,

189
00:24:08,997 --> 00:24:11,432
the ones closest to my age,

190
00:24:11,758 --> 00:24:13,989
the most romantic was Guilhermina,

191
00:24:15,439 --> 00:24:17,431
and we were sweethearts.

192
00:24:32,445 --> 00:24:35,483
At night I used to go upstairs
to meet her,

193
00:24:35,925 --> 00:24:38,487
careful not to wake anyone.

194
00:24:40,847 --> 00:24:43,043
These were
our very green years and,

195
00:24:43,248 --> 00:24:47,606
with the innocence of children,
we would exchange a pure kiss...

196
00:24:50,650 --> 00:24:51,605
Careful!

197
00:25:00,212 --> 00:25:04,002
And immediately run off in fright
to our respective bedrooms,

198
00:25:04,534 --> 00:25:10,771
carrying with us the delight of
that sweet and innocent adventure.

199
00:25:12,097 --> 00:25:13,248
Time passed.
Guilhermina disappeared forever,

200
00:25:15,698 --> 00:25:18,815
with tuberculosis, like her brother.
The houses are now different,

201
00:25:19,418 --> 00:25:22,456
only the memory of the brief
encounter has remained.

202
00:25:24,420 --> 00:25:26,776
And in this old Crystal Palace

203
00:25:27,021 --> 00:25:31,892
they continued to have
a Motor Show every autumn.

204
00:25:41,506 --> 00:25:43,736
We were in 1922,

205
00:25:44,106 --> 00:25:47,816
the date of the
Lisbon-Rio Atlantic crossing

206
00:25:48,107 --> 00:25:51,259
for the first time
in the history of aviation,

207
00:25:51,668 --> 00:25:58,622
with the sextant of Gago Coutinho and
Sacadura Cabral flying this plane.

208
00:26:08,193 --> 00:26:10,071
Somewhat later on

209
00:26:10,314 --> 00:26:13,432
a branch of the Confeitaria Oliveira
opened here

210
00:26:13,675 --> 00:26:16,236
in the Rua 31 de Janeiro,

211
00:26:16,476 --> 00:26:20,265
the date commemorating
the Oporto Movement,

212
00:26:20,557 --> 00:26:25,428
the first attempt to set up
a republic in Portugal.

213
00:26:26,919 --> 00:26:31,915
The shop window was protected
by a thick yellow metal rail,

214
00:26:33,041 --> 00:26:36,751
against which certain bohemians
used to lean in the afternoon...

215
00:26:37,163 --> 00:26:41,076
bohemians who were... raffinés.
- Raffinés... and a little pedantic!

216
00:26:42,404 --> 00:26:45,761
Raffiné... was Joel,
with his monocle.

217
00:26:46,605 --> 00:26:50,315
And Diogo, who always
came along in uniform

218
00:26:50,566 --> 00:26:52,603
and acting like a lady-killer.

219
00:26:52,967 --> 00:26:56,563
The youngest one, Chico,
had a certain blasé air.

220
00:26:57,008 --> 00:27:02,562
- Blasé... Very blasé...
- We nicknamed him ''Fantasias''.

221
00:27:03,810 --> 00:27:06,769
Fantasias thought
it was of no interest

222
00:27:06,971 --> 00:27:10,248
to carry on living
after the age of forty.

223
00:27:10,493 --> 00:27:13,610
I think it is really inelegant
for a man to let himself grow old.

224
00:27:13,853 --> 00:27:16,607
Longevity was shorter
in those days,

225
00:27:16,974 --> 00:27:20,126
and forty was a ripe old age.

226
00:27:22,456 --> 00:27:24,846
That's what you say,
but you don't know why you say it.

227
00:27:25,057 --> 00:27:28,607
- Oh, yeah? I say what I feel.
- But you don't know what you feel.

228
00:27:29,858 --> 00:27:31,337
And you do?

229
00:27:34,100 --> 00:27:38,139
- I think there is a reason.
- You think so? Well explain it.

230
00:27:39,021 --> 00:27:43,254
It's simple.
Men like women, don't they?

231
00:27:45,342 --> 00:27:47,938
And women like men, don't they?

232
00:27:50,264 --> 00:27:52,301
I think we've understood that!

233
00:27:53,865 --> 00:27:55,902
Before there used
to be the androgen,

234
00:27:56,147 --> 00:27:58,262
which included the masculine
and the feminine.

235
00:28:00,028 --> 00:28:01,585
They were happy!

236
00:28:02,708 --> 00:28:04,984
So? What do you mean by that?

237
00:28:05,949 --> 00:28:09,660
That when they were together they
didn't have to look for each other.

238
00:28:12,111 --> 00:28:13,430
How dull...

239
00:28:15,432 --> 00:28:18,311
You think it's dull?
That's the way it was.

